{"type":"message","id":"4c5f3bb8","parentId":"9b23eb26","timestamp":"2026-02-19T18:27:49.141Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Examining Directory Creation**\n\nI've realized that the initial `mkdir` failure stemmed from a difference in how PowerShell handles the command compared to bash. Specifically, the `-p` flag wasn't behaving as expected. Consequently, the directories were not created. I should either use `New-Item` with the `-ItemType Directory` flag and a comma-separated list of paths or rely on the `write` tool to create the directories. The files I wanted created were written with the `write` tool.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771525668906_38","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -R configs src utils"},"thoughtSignature":""},{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Troubleshooting File Existence**\n\nI'm now investigating file creation. The `write` tool, invoked for file creation, should have also handled directory creation automatically. I need to verify that those files do indeed exist, as this would impact the outcome. After confirming the files, I will run the `auto_doc.py` script and check the README's update to match.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771525669137_39","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python auto_doc.py"}}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":7344,"output":273,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":7617,"cost":{"input":0.014688,"output":0.0032760000000000003,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.017964}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771525641405}}
